   <m:mtext>V</m:mtext>
  </m:mrow>
 </m:semantics>
</m:math>.</para></example>
</section>
<section id="fs-id1502616" class="section-summary"><title>Section Summary</title><list id="fs-id1010245"><item id="import-auto-id1534698">Capacitors are used in a variety of devices, including defibrillators, microelectronics such as calculators, and flash lamps, to supply energy.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id1611426">The energy stored in a capacitor can be expressed in three ways:
    <equation id="eip-635"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>cap</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mstyle fontstyle="italic"><m:mrow><m:mtext>QV</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mstyle><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mtext fontstyle="italic">CV</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:msup><m:mi>Q</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>C</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mfrac></m:mrow><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{E rSub { size 8{"cap"} } = {  { ital "QV"}  over  {2} } = {  { ital "CV" rSup { size 8{2} } }  over  {2} } = {  {Q rSup { size 8{2} } }  over  {2C} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></equation>
where
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>Q</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{Q} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math><emphasis effect="italics"/> is the charge, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>V</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{V} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is the voltage, and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>C</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{C} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is the capacitance of the capacitor. The energy is in joules when the charge is in coulombs, voltage is in volts, and capacitance is in farads.</item>
</list></section><section id="fs-id1945775" class="conceptual-questions" type="conceptual-questions">
